const SEC_HLD = {
  id:"hld",title:"HLD & System Design",icon:"🏗",ib:"rgba(163,117,255,.15)",ic:"#a378ff",
  grp:"arch",bar:"#a378ff",tglow:"rgba(163,117,255,.09)",
  desc:"Circuit breaker, Saga, distributed locking, rate limiting, CAP, CQRS, outbox, and classic system design problems.",
  tags:["Circuit breaker","Saga","CAP","CQRS","Outbox","Rate limiter","Sharding"],
  qs:[
    {q:"What is the circuit breaker pattern and how are its states defined?",d:"hard", id:1,
     a:"The circuit breaker prevents <em>cascading failures</em> — if a downstream service is slow or failing, don't keep sending requests that will all fail and waste resources.<br><br><strong>States:</strong><br><br><strong>Closed</strong> (normal): requests flow through. Failures are counted. When the failure rate exceeds a threshold (e.g., 50% of last 10 calls) → Open.<br><br><strong>Open</strong> (tripped): requests fail immediately without calling the downstream service. Returns a pre-defined fallback. After a wait duration (e.g., 30s) → Half-Open.<br><br><strong>Half-Open</strong> (probing): a limited number of test requests are allowed through. If they succeed → Closed. If they fail → Open again.<br><br><strong>Resilience4j implementation:</strong><br><pre>@CircuitBreaker(name = \"paymentService\", fallbackMethod = \"payFallback\")\npublic PaymentResult charge(Order order) { ... }\n\npublic PaymentResult payFallback(Order order, Exception e) {\n  return PaymentResult.deferred(order.getId());\n}</pre><br>Configure: <code>slidingWindowSize=10</code>, <code>failureRateThreshold=50</code>, <code>waitDurationInOpenState=30s</code>, <code>permittedCallsInHalfOpenState=3</code>."},

    {q:"What is the Saga pattern for distributed transactions?",d:"hard", id:2,
     a:"Sagas break a long-running distributed transaction into a sequence of local transactions, each with a <strong>compensating transaction</strong> to undo it on failure — without 2PC (two-phase commit).<br><br><strong>Example — Order flow:</strong> Reserve inventory → Charge payment → Create shipment → Confirm order.<br><strong>Compensations:</strong> Release inventory ← Refund payment ← Cancel shipment.<br><br><strong>Choreography:</strong> each service publishes an event that triggers the next service. No central coordinator.<ul><li>✅ Simple, loosely coupled</li><li>❌ Hard to track overall state, easy to lose track of failures</li></ul><br><strong>Orchestration:</strong> a central Saga Orchestrator sends commands to each service and handles compensation on failure.<ul><li>✅ Clear flow, easier to monitor and debug</li><li>❌ Central coordinator adds complexity (Temporal, Conductor, or custom)</li></ul><br><strong>Key rule:</strong> compensating transactions must be idempotent (safe to retry). Design your system so each step can be rolled back cleanly."},

    {q:"What is the CAP theorem and how do real databases choose?",d:"hard", id:3,
     a:"In a distributed system during a network partition, you can only guarantee 2 of these 3 properties:<br><br><strong>Consistency (C):</strong> every read sees the most recent write (or an error).<br><strong>Availability (A):</strong> every request gets a non-error response (though it may be stale).<br><strong>Partition tolerance (P):</strong> the system continues to operate despite network partitions.<br><br>Since network partitions are unavoidable in production distributed systems, P is non-negotiable. The real choice is <strong>CP vs AP</strong>:<br><br><strong>CP systems</strong> (prefer consistency over availability during partition):<ul><li>PostgreSQL with synchronous replication, HBase, Zookeeper, etcd</li><li>Will return an error rather than serve stale data</li></ul><br><strong>AP systems</strong> (prefer availability over consistency during partition):<ul><li>Cassandra, DynamoDB, CouchDB, Redis Cluster</li><li>Will return stale data rather than error</li></ul><br><strong>PACELC extension:</strong> even without partition, choose between Latency and Consistency — asynchronous replication = lower latency but eventual consistency."},

    {q:"What is CQRS and when should you use it?",d:"hard", id:4,
     a:"<strong>CQRS</strong> (Command Query Responsibility Segregation) separates the write model (Commands that modify state) from the read model (Queries that return data).<br><br><strong>Write side:</strong> domain model optimised for business rules and consistency — normalised, validated, transactional.<br><br><strong>Read side:</strong> one or more dedicated read models optimised per query pattern — denormalised, pre-aggregated, potentially different data store (read from ElasticSearch, Redis, or a denormalised DB table).<br><br><strong>Synchronisation:</strong> when a command changes state, publish a domain event → read model subscribes and updates itself (eventually consistent).<br><br><strong>Benefits:</strong> independently scale reads and writes; optimise read performance without compromising write correctness; multiple projections for different clients.<br><br><strong>Costs:</strong> eventual consistency between write and read models; significant added complexity; needs event infrastructure.<br><br><strong>When to use:</strong> high read/write ratio difference, complex domain with many query patterns, or when combined with Event Sourcing. <strong>Do not apply by default</strong> to simple CRUD services."},

    {q:"What is the outbox pattern and why is it necessary?",d:"hard", id:5,
     a:"<strong>Problem without outbox:</strong><br><pre>// In a transaction:\norderRepository.save(order);       // DB write succeeds\nkafkaTemplate.send(\"orders\", event); // Kafka publish fails!\n// DB has the order but no event was published → inconsistency</pre><br>Or the reverse: event published, then DB save fails.<br><br><strong>Outbox pattern solution:</strong> write the event to an <code>outbox</code> table <em>in the same DB transaction</em> as the business change:<br><pre>@Transactional\npublic void placeOrder(Order order) {\n  orderRepository.save(order);\n  outboxRepository.save(new OutboxEvent(\n    \"OrderPlaced\", toJson(order)));\n  // Single atomic DB transaction — both or neither\n}</pre><br>A separate <strong>relay process</strong> reads unprocessed outbox entries and publishes to Kafka, then marks them processed.<br><br><strong>Relay implementations:</strong><ul><li><strong>Debezium (CDC):</strong> reads from PostgreSQL WAL directly — zero-latency, no polling overhead. Most production-grade.</li><li><strong>Scheduled poller:</strong> simple but adds latency</li></ul>Guarantees: event is published if and only if the DB transaction committed."},

    {q:"How would you design a URL shortener at scale?",d:"hard", id:6,
     a:"<strong>Requirements:</strong> shorten long URLs, redirect short → long, handle ~100M URLs, ~1B redirects/day.<br><br><strong>ID generation:</strong> generate a unique short code. Options:<ul><li>Base62 encode a distributed unique ID (Snowflake / Redis INCR)</li><li>7 chars of Base62 = 62⁷ = 3.5 trillion unique codes</li></ul><br><strong>Write path:</strong><ol><li>Validate long URL</li><li>Generate short code</li><li>Store <code>shortCode → longURL</code> in PostgreSQL/DynamoDB</li><li>Cache in Redis (long TTL — most shorts never expire)</li><li>Return short URL</li></ol><br><strong>Read path (hot path — must be fast):</strong><ol><li>Redis cache lookup (expected hit rate >95%)</li><li>DB fallback on miss</li><li>HTTP 302 redirect to long URL</li></ol><br><strong>Scale estimates:</strong><ul><li>1B redirects/day = ~11,600 req/s</li><li>Storage: 100M × ~100 bytes/entry = ~10GB</li><li>Read replicas + CDN for global latency</li></ul><br><strong>Analytics:</strong> async via Kafka → ClickHouse/BigQuery."},

    {q:"What is the rate limiter algorithm design?",d:"hard", id:7,
     a:"<strong>Token Bucket:</strong> bucket capacity B, refilled at rate R tokens/sec. Request consumes 1 token. Allows bursts up to B while enforcing average rate R. Most common and flexible.<br><br><strong>Fixed Window Counter:</strong> count requests per fixed window (e.g., per minute). Simple. Vulnerability: 100 req at 11:59:59 + 100 req at 12:00:00 = 200 req in 2 seconds (2× limit).<br><br><strong>Sliding Window Log:</strong> store timestamp of each request in a sorted set. Count entries in last 60s. Accurate but O(requests) memory.<br><br><strong>Sliding Window Counter:</strong> blend current window count with previous window count weighted by the fraction of overlap. Efficient approximation: <code>count = prev × (1 - elapsed/window) + curr</code><br><br><strong>Leaky Bucket:</strong> requests are processed at a constant rate from a queue (leaks at fixed rate). Smooths output. Queue overflow = rejection.<br><br><strong>Recommendation for backend APIs:</strong> Token Bucket (Bucket4j library) for per-user limits; Sliding Window Counter for global API limits. Store state in Redis for distributed consistency across multiple service instances."},

    {q:"What is event-driven architecture and what are its trade-offs?",d:"hard", id:8,
     a:"Services communicate by publishing and consuming events asynchronously rather than making direct synchronous calls.<br><br><strong>Benefits:</strong><ul><li><strong>Loose coupling:</strong> the order service doesn't know about the email service — it just publishes <code>OrderPlaced</code></li><li><strong>Independent scaling:</strong> consumers scale independently based on their queue depth</li><li><strong>Natural audit log:</strong> all state changes are events — replay for debugging or migrating to a new system</li><li><strong>Resilience:</strong> producer and consumer can be independently down without losing events</li></ul><br><strong>Trade-offs:</strong><ul><li><strong>Eventual consistency:</strong> the email service may process the event seconds/minutes after the order was placed — design your UI for this</li><li><strong>Duplicate handling:</strong> at-least-once delivery means consumers must be idempotent</li><li><strong>Debugging complexity:</strong> a request's journey spans multiple services — distributed tracing is essential</li><li><strong>Schema evolution:</strong> published events are a shared API — breaking changes require careful versioning</li></ul><br>Use the <strong>outbox pattern</strong> to ensure events are reliably published."},

    {q:"How would you design a distributed job scheduler?",d:"hard", id:9,
     a:"<strong>Requirements:</strong> run jobs at scheduled times, exactly-once execution across N distributed instances, retry on failure, history.<br><br><strong>Simple approach (low scale):</strong> use Spring's <code>@Scheduled</code> + a distributed lock (Shedlock library):<br><pre>@Scheduled(cron = \"0 0 * * * *\")\n@SchedulerLock(name = \"hourlyReport\", lockAtMostFor = \"50m\")\npublic void runHourlyReport() { ... }</pre>ShedLock stores the lock in a DB table — guarantees only one instance runs per scheduled time.<br><br><strong>Production approach:</strong> use <strong>Quartz Scheduler</strong> (clustered mode, DB-backed) — stores job triggers in a DB, multiple nodes compete for triggers using row-level locking. Handles misfires (missed executions).<br><br><strong>Advanced workflows:</strong> <strong>Temporal</strong> or <strong>Conductor</strong> — full workflow orchestration with retry, state persistence, and visibility. Ideal for long-running, multi-step jobs.<br><br><strong>Key concerns to address:</strong> at-most-once execution, idempotent job logic, retry with backoff, job history and monitoring, alerting on failures."},

    {q:"What is the difference between horizontal and vertical scaling?",d:"easy", id:10,
     a:"<strong>Vertical scaling (scale up):</strong> add more CPU/RAM/disk to the existing machine.<ul><li>✅ Simple — no code changes, no distributed system complexity</li><li>✅ Strong consistency — one machine = no distributed state</li><li>❌ Has physical limits</li><li>❌ Single point of failure</li><li>❌ Downtime required for upgrade (usually)</li><li>❌ Exponentially more expensive at the high end</li></ul><br><strong>Horizontal scaling (scale out):</strong> add more machines behind a load balancer.<ul><li>✅ Near-unlimited scale</li><li>✅ Fault tolerant — instance failures don't take down the system</li><li>✅ Pay-as-you-grow in cloud</li><li>❌ Requires stateless application design</li><li>❌ Needs distributed session (Redis), distributed locking, distributed caching</li><li>❌ More operational complexity</li></ul><br><strong>Cloud-native design principle:</strong> design for horizontal scaling from day one — build stateless services, externalise state to managed services (Redis, RDS, S3)."},

    {q:"What is a load balancer and what algorithms does it use?",d:"medium", id:11,
     a:"A load balancer distributes incoming requests across multiple backend instances to prevent any single instance from being overloaded.<br><br><strong>Algorithms:</strong><ul><li><strong>Round Robin:</strong> sequentially distribute requests 1-2-3-1-2-3. Simple. Assumes all instances have equal capacity.</li><li><strong>Weighted Round Robin:</strong> assign more requests to higher-capacity instances.</li><li><strong>Least Connections:</strong> route to the instance with the fewest active connections. Better for variable-cost requests (e.g., file uploads).</li><li><strong>IP Hash:</strong> <code>hash(client_IP) % n</code> → same client always hits same server. Soft session affinity — breaks if an instance is removed.</li><li><strong>Random:</strong> statistically approaches Round Robin at scale.</li></ul><br><strong>Layer 4 (TCP) LB:</strong> routes by IP/port. Fast, no HTTP understanding. NLB in AWS.<br><br><strong>Layer 7 (HTTP) LB:</strong> inspects HTTP headers, path, host — enables path-based routing, header-based routing, A/B testing. ALB in AWS.<br><br><strong>Health checks:</strong> LB probes each instance and removes unhealthy ones from rotation automatically."}
  ]
};

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"How would you design a real-time chat system?",d:"hard", id:12,
     a:"<strong>Core requirements:</strong> low-latency message delivery, message persistence, online presence, group chats, read receipts.<br><br><strong>Connection layer:</strong> WebSocket for persistent, bidirectional connections (HTTP long-polling as fallback). Each WebSocket server holds a map of <code>userId → WebSocket session</code>.<br><br><strong>Message flow:</strong><ol><li>Sender sends message via WebSocket to connection server</li><li>Connection server publishes to Kafka topic <code>chat.messages</code></li><li>Kafka consumer (or same server) finds recipient's connection server via Redis key <code>user:{id}:server</code></li><li>Delivers message via WebSocket to recipient</li><li>If offline: store in DB for retrieval on next login</li></ol><br><strong>Persistence:</strong> Cassandra or DynamoDB — optimised for time-series message retrieval by conversation ID. Schema: <code>partition key = conversation_id, sort key = created_at</code>.<br><br><strong>Presence:</strong> Redis key <code>online:{userId}</code> with 30s TTL, refreshed via heartbeat. <code>SUBSCRIBE channel:{userId}</code> for real-time presence events.<br><br><strong>Scale:</strong> 1M concurrent users × 1 msg/10s = 100,000 msgs/sec — manageable with Kafka + horizontal WebSocket servers."},

  {q:"What is the two-phase commit (2PC) and why is it avoided in microservices?",d:"hard", id:13,
     a:"<strong>2PC</strong> coordinates a distributed transaction across multiple resources (DBs, message brokers) to achieve atomicity.<br><br><strong>Phase 1 (Prepare):</strong> coordinator sends PREPARE to all participants. Each participant executes the transaction locally, logs to WAL, and responds READY or ABORT.<br><br><strong>Phase 2 (Commit/Abort):</strong> if all said READY → coordinator sends COMMIT to all. If any said ABORT → coordinator sends ROLLBACK.<br><br><strong>Why avoided in microservices:</strong><ul><li><strong>Blocking protocol:</strong> participants hold locks from Prepare until Commit — can block for seconds if coordinator fails</li><li><strong>Coordinator SPOF:</strong> if coordinator dies after Prepare but before Commit, participants are stuck with resources locked (in-doubt transaction)</li><li><strong>Tight coupling:</strong> all services must support the same XA transaction coordinator</li><li><strong>Poor availability:</strong> any participant failure blocks the entire transaction</li></ul><br><strong>Microservices alternatives:</strong><ul><li><strong>Saga pattern</strong> — choreography or orchestration with compensating transactions</li><li><strong>Outbox pattern</strong> — local transaction + event relay</li><li><strong>Idempotent at-least-once</strong> — accept eventual consistency</li></ul>"},

  {q:"How would you design a search autocomplete system?",d:"hard", id:14,
     a:"<strong>Requirements:</strong> sub-100ms suggestions as user types, top-N results by frequency/relevance, updates as trends change.<br><br><strong>Data structure — Trie:</strong> prefix tree where each path from root to node represents a prefix. Each terminal node stores frequency count. But a pure trie doesn't rank well at scale.<br><br><strong>Production approach — Redis Sorted Sets:</strong><br><pre>// For every prefix of \"iphone\", store term with score = frequency\n// \"i\" → {\"iphone\":1000, \"ipad\":900, \"instagram\":800}\n// \"ip\" → {\"iphone\":1000, \"ipad\":900, \"ipod\":400}\n\n// Query: user types \"ip\"\nredis.zrevrange(\"autocomplete:ip\", 0, 9) // top 10</pre><br><strong>Trie + heap approach:</strong> build a trie in memory (or distributed trie), each node stores a min-heap of top-K terms with their frequencies. Querying a prefix returns the heap immediately — O(prefix_length).<br><br><strong>Elasticsearch:</strong> <code>completion</code> field type with built-in prefix suggestion, FST-based, very fast. Best for production when you already use ES.<br><br><strong>Update frequency counts:</strong> batch from analytics pipeline (hourly/daily) — avoid real-time writes to keep read path fast."}
);

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"How would you design a payment processing system?",d:"hard", id:15,
     a:"<strong>Key requirements:</strong> exactly-once processing, auditability, compliance, idempotency, fraud detection, multiple payment methods.<br><br><strong>Core components:</strong><ol><li><strong>API Gateway:</strong> rate limiting, auth, idempotency key validation</li><li><strong>Payment Service:</strong> orchestrates the payment flow</li><li><strong>Ledger Service:</strong> double-entry bookkeeping — every debit has a credit</li><li><strong>Payment Processor Adapters:</strong> Stripe, PayPal, bank APIs</li><li><strong>Fraud Detection Service:</strong> async risk scoring</li><li><strong>Notification Service:</strong> success/failure emails</li></ol><br><strong>Critical patterns:</strong><ul><li><strong>Idempotency key:</strong> UUID per payment — prevents double charge on retry</li><li><strong>State machine:</strong> PENDING → PROCESSING → COMPLETED/FAILED/REFUNDED. Store every transition.</li><li><strong>Outbox pattern:</strong> write payment + event in same DB transaction</li><li><strong>Saga for multi-party payments:</strong> reserve funds → charge → release</li></ul><br><strong>Data model:</strong><br><pre>payments: id, idempotency_key, amount, currency, status, created_at\npayment_events: id, payment_id, event_type, data, created_at\nledger_entries: id, payment_id, account, amount, type (DEBIT/CREDIT)</pre><br>Every operation is append-only — never update; always insert a new state event."},

  {q:"What is consistent hashing and when do you use it?",d:"hard", id:16,
     a:"Consistent hashing minimises the number of key remappings when nodes are added or removed from a distributed system — critical for caches and distributed databases.<br><br><strong>The problem with naive modulo hashing:</strong> with N servers and hash(key) % N, adding/removing a server requires remapping almost ALL keys.<br><br><strong>Consistent hashing solution:</strong><ol><li>Arrange all possible hashes in a circle (ring) from 0 to 2³²</li><li>Hash each server to one (or multiple) positions on the ring</li><li>For each key, hash it and walk clockwise to the first server node</li></ol><br>Adding/removing one server only remaps keys that were assigned to that server — typically 1/N of all keys.<br><br><strong>Virtual nodes</strong> (vnodes): each physical server has K virtual positions on the ring (typically 150). This balances load evenly even with heterogeneous servers and handles \"hotspot\" positions.<br><br><strong>Real-world use:</strong><ul><li>Redis Cluster hash slot allocation</li><li>Cassandra token ring</li><li>CDN request routing to edge servers</li><li>Consistent routing in API gateways</li></ul><br>Java library: <code>ketama</code> or implement with <code>TreeMap.ceilingKey(hash)</code>."},

  {q:"How would you design a distributed notification system with priorities?",d:"hard", id:17,
     a:"<strong>Requirements:</strong> send email/SMS/push across millions of users, priority queuing (transactional > marketing), rate limiting per user/channel, deduplication, delivery tracking.<br><br><strong>Architecture:</strong><br><pre>API → Kafka topic: notifications.inbound\n  ↓\nNotification Router (consumer)\n  ├── Kafka: notifications.high-priority   (payments, OTPs)\n  ├── Kafka: notifications.normal          (order updates)\n  └── Kafka: notifications.low-priority    (promotions)\n         ↓\nChannel Workers (separate consumer groups per channel)\n  ├── Email Worker → SendGrid\n  ├── SMS Worker → Twilio\n  └── Push Worker → FCM/APNs</pre><br><strong>Key design decisions:</strong><ul><li><strong>Priority:</strong> separate Kafka topics per priority level — high priority topics have more consumer instances</li><li><strong>Rate limiting per user:</strong> Redis: max 3 SMS/day, 10 emails/day per user. Check before dispatching.</li><li><strong>Deduplication:</strong> Redis SET with TTL keyed by <code>notification:{userId}:{contentHash}</code> — prevent sending the same message twice</li><li><strong>User preferences:</strong> cache channel opt-in/opt-out in Redis; update from DB async</li><li><strong>Delivery tracking:</strong> write delivery status events back to Kafka; store in Cassandra for querying</li></ul>"},

  {q:"What is the database-per-service pattern and how do you handle cross-service queries?",d:"hard", id:18,
     a:"Each microservice owns its own private database — no other service queries it directly. This enables independent scaling, schema evolution, and technology choice per service.<br><br><strong>Problem this creates:</strong> you can't JOIN across service boundaries. A query like \"get all orders with customer names\" can't use a SQL JOIN if orders and customers are in different databases.<br><br><strong>Solution patterns:</strong><br><br><strong>1. API Composition:</strong> orchestrator calls both services and joins in application code:<br><pre>// Order service returns orders with customerId\n// Orchestrator enriches with customer name from Customer service\nList&lt;Order&gt; orders = orderService.getByStatus(status);\nSet&lt;Long&gt; customerIds = orders.stream()\n  .map(Order::getCustomerId).collect(toSet());\nMap&lt;Long, Customer&gt; customers = customerService.findByIds(customerIds);\n// Merge in memory</pre><br><strong>2. CQRS read model:</strong> maintain a denormalised read table in one service, updated via events from both services. Fast queries, eventual consistency.<br><br><strong>3. GraphQL Federation:</strong> each service owns its type; the gateway resolves cross-service fields transparently.<br><br>The tradeoff is always eventual consistency vs strong isolation. Design for it explicitly."},

  {q:"What is the two-generals problem and how does it relate to distributed systems?",d:"hard", id:19,
     a:"The Two Generals Problem is a classic thought experiment: two armies must attack simultaneously to win, but their only communication channel (messengers) is unreliable — messengers can be captured. It's impossible to achieve guaranteed coordinated action over an unreliable channel.<br><br><strong>Implication for distributed systems:</strong> it's provably impossible to achieve guaranteed agreement between two parties over an unreliable network. You cannot have both:<ul><li>Guaranteed delivery</li><li>Guaranteed knowledge that the other party received the message</li></ul><br><strong>Real-world manifestations:</strong><ul><li>HTTP: you POST a payment — network drops the response. Did it succeed? You don't know without retrying.</li><li>Kafka: producer receives a timeout — was the message committed to the broker or not?</li><li>Database replication: primary acknowledged a commit — did all replicas receive it before primary crashed?</li></ul><br><strong>Practical solutions:</strong><ul><li><strong>Idempotency keys:</strong> safe to retry — server deduplicates</li><li><strong>At-least-once delivery + idempotent consumers</strong></li><li><strong>Sagas with compensations</strong> instead of distributed transactions</li><li><strong>Accept eventual consistency</strong> — design the system around it</li></ul>"},

  {q:"How do you implement observability (logs, metrics, traces) in a microservices system?",d:"hard", id:20,
     a:"Observability means being able to understand the internal state of a system from its external outputs. The three pillars:<br><br><strong>Logs — structured JSON:</strong><br><pre>{\n  \"timestamp\": \"2024-01-15T10:30:00Z\",\n  \"level\": \"INFO\",\n  \"service\": \"order-service\",\n  \"traceId\": \"abc123\",\n  \"spanId\": \"def456\",\n  \"userId\": \"user-789\",\n  \"message\": \"Order created\",\n  \"orderId\": \"ord-001\"\n}</pre>Ship to Elasticsearch/Loki. Query by traceId to see all logs for one request across all services.<br><br><strong>Metrics — Prometheus + Grafana:</strong><br><pre>management.metrics.export.prometheus.enabled=true\n\n# Key metrics to track:\n# http_server_requests_seconds (latency + rate + errors)\n# jvm_memory_used_bytes (heap usage)\n# hikaricp_connections_active (DB pool)\n# kafka.consumer.lag (consumer health)</pre><br>Alert on: error rate > 1%, p99 latency > 500ms, consumer lag growing.<br><br><strong>Traces — Micrometer + Grafana Tempo/Jaeger:</strong> correlate logs + traces via traceId in MDC. Set sampling to 10% in production, 100% for errors.<br><br><strong>SLO/SLA dashboards:</strong> track availability (% of requests returning 2xx) and latency (p50/p95/p99) per endpoint."}
);

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"How would you design a payment processing system?",d:"hard", id:21,
     a:"<strong>Core requirements:</strong> process payments, prevent double charges, handle failures, PCI compliance, refunds, audit trail.<br><br><strong>Key components:</strong><ul><li><strong>Payment API:</strong> accepts charge requests with idempotency keys</li><li><strong>Payment Orchestrator:</strong> manages the flow: validate → acquire → settle</li><strong>State machine per payment:</strong> PENDING → PROCESSING → SUCCEEDED / FAILED / REFUNDED</li></ul><br><strong>Idempotency:</strong><br><pre>POST /payments\nIdempotency-Key: client-generated-uuid\n{\"amount\": 100, \"currency\": \"USD\", \"paymentMethodId\": \"pm_xxx\"}\n\n// Server: check idempotency key in Redis/DB before processing\n// Return cached result if already processed</pre><br><strong>Double-charge prevention:</strong> distributed lock on (userId + orderId) during processing. DB unique constraint on idempotency key.<br><br><strong>Failure handling:</strong><ul><li>Timeout: payment may have succeeded on gateway but response lost — query gateway status before retry</li><li>Partial failure: rollback via compensating transactions (refund)</li></ul><br><strong>Outbox pattern:</strong> write payment event to outbox table in same DB transaction → relay to Kafka → downstream services (email, inventory, analytics).<br><br><strong>Compliance:</strong> never store raw card numbers — tokenise via gateway. Log all payment state transitions for audit."},

  {q:"What is consistent hashing and how does it help with scaling?",d:"hard", id:22,
     a:"<strong>Problem with naive sharding:</strong> <code>shard = key % N</code>. When you add a node (N becomes N+1), almost all keys map to different shards — massive data reshuffling.<br><br><strong>Consistent hashing solution:</strong><ol><li>Map both nodes AND keys to positions on a conceptual ring (0 to 2³²)</li><li>A key is assigned to the first node clockwise from its ring position</li><li>Adding a node: only keys between the new node and its predecessor move — ~K/N keys (minimal disruption)</li><li>Removing a node: only that node's keys move to the next node clockwise</li></ol><br><strong>Virtual nodes (vnodes):</strong> each physical node has 150+ virtual positions on the ring. This ensures even distribution even with heterogeneous node capacities, and smaller data movement per node change.<br><br><strong>Real-world usage:</strong><ul><li>Cassandra and DynamoDB use consistent hashing for data distribution</li><li>Redis Cluster uses hash slots (16,384) — similar concept</li><li>CDN cache routing</li><li>Distributed caches (Memcached with ketama hashing)</li></ul><br><strong>Java implementation:</strong> use a <code>TreeMap</code> where keys are node hash positions — <code>ceilingKey(hashOfData)</code> finds the first node clockwise."},

  {q:"What is event sourcing and how does it differ from traditional CRUD?",d:"hard", id:23,
     a:"<strong>Traditional CRUD:</strong> store current state. When something changes, UPDATE the row — the previous state is lost.<br><br><strong>Event Sourcing:</strong> never mutate state — instead, append an immutable event for every change. The current state is derived by replaying all events from the beginning.<br><pre>// Events are the source of truth:\nOrderCreated    { orderId, customerId, items, createdAt }\nOrderPaid       { orderId, amount, paymentId, paidAt }\nOrderShipped    { orderId, trackingNumber, shippedAt }\nOrderCancelled  { orderId, reason, cancelledAt }\n\n// Current state = replay all events:\nOrder current = eventStore.findByOrderId(id)\n  .stream()\n  .reduce(new Order(), Order::apply);</pre><br><strong>Benefits:</strong><ul><li>Full audit trail — every change recorded with timestamp and context</li><li>Time travel — reconstruct state at any point in time</li><li>Event replay — rebuild projections, debug issues, migrate to new data model</li><li>Natural integration — events published to Kafka for downstream consumers</li></ul><br><strong>Challenges:</strong><ul><li>Query complexity — need to maintain read projections (CQRS is natural companion)</li><li>Eventual consistency between event store and projections</li><li>Event schema evolution — old events must still be playable with new code</li></ul>"},

  {q:"What is observability and what are the three pillars?",d:"medium", id:24,
     a:"<strong>Observability</strong> is the ability to understand the internal state of a system purely from its external outputs — enabling you to ask new questions without deploying new code.<br><br><strong>The Three Pillars:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Logs:</strong> timestamped records of discrete events.<ul><li>Structured logging (JSON) — machine parseable: <code>{\"level\":\"ERROR\",\"message\":\"...\",\"traceId\":\"abc\"}</code></li><li>Tools: ELK Stack (Elasticsearch + Logstash + Kibana), Grafana Loki, CloudWatch Logs</li><li>Correlation: inject traceId + requestId into MDC for cross-service log correlation</li></ul><br><strong>2. Metrics:</strong> aggregated numeric measurements over time.<ul><li>Counters (requests total), Gauges (active connections), Histograms (latency percentiles)</li><li>Tools: Prometheus + Grafana, Datadog, CloudWatch Metrics</li><li>Spring Boot: Micrometer auto-instruments JVM, HTTP, DB, Kafka metrics</li></ul><br><strong>3. Traces:</strong> end-to-end view of a single request across multiple services.<ul><li>Propagate traceId/spanId via HTTP headers (W3C TraceContext)</li><li>Tools: Jaeger, Zipkin, Grafana Tempo, Datadog APM</li><li>Spring Boot 3: Micrometer Tracing auto-instruments everything</li></ul><br><strong>Golden signals</strong> (Google SRE): Latency, Traffic, Errors, Saturation — monitor these four metrics for any service."}
);

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"How would you design a payment system?",d:"hard", id:25,
     a:"<strong>Core requirements:</strong> process payments reliably, prevent double charges, handle failures gracefully, full audit trail.<br><br><strong>Key design decisions:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Idempotency at every step:</strong><br><pre>POST /payments\nIdempotency-Key: client-generated-uuid\n{ \"orderId\": \"abc\", \"amount\": 99.99, \"currency\": \"USD\" }</pre>Store result by idempotency key. Retries return the same result.<br><br><strong>2. State machine for payment lifecycle:</strong><br><code>INITIATED → PROCESSING → COMPLETED | FAILED | REFUNDED</code><br><br><strong>3. Outbox pattern for event publishing:</strong> write payment record and outbox event in one DB transaction. Relay publishes to Kafka.<br><br><strong>4. External payment provider integration:</strong><ul><li>Call Stripe/PayPal with idempotency key</li><li>Handle timeouts — unknown state — poll provider for status</li><li>3-state commit: initiated / confirmed / failed</li></ul><br><strong>5. Reconciliation job:</strong> nightly compare your DB records with provider statements — catch any discrepancies.<br><br><strong>6. Double-spend prevention:</strong> pessimistic lock on the wallet/account row during deduction, or use a versioned balance with optimistic locking."},

  {q:"What is consistent hashing and where is it used?",d:"hard", id:26,
     a:"<strong>Problem:</strong> with N cache servers, a simple <code>hash(key) % N</code> scheme remaps almost all keys when N changes (add/remove server) — massive cache misses.<br><br><strong>Consistent hashing:</strong> maps both servers and keys to positions on a virtual ring (0 to 2³²). A key is assigned to the first server clockwise from its position.<br><br><strong>When a server is added/removed:</strong> only the keys between the new server and its predecessor need to move — on average <code>K/N</code> keys instead of nearly all of them.<br><br><strong>Virtual nodes:</strong> each physical server is represented by multiple virtual nodes on the ring (e.g., 150 virtual nodes per server). This ensures even distribution even with servers of different capacities.<br><pre>// Conceptual in Java:\nTreeMap&lt;Integer, String&gt; ring = new TreeMap&lt;&gt;();\n// Add server at multiple virtual points\nIntStream.range(0, 150).forEach(i -&gt;\n  ring.put(hash(server + \"#\" + i), server));\n\n// Find server for key\nMap.Entry&lt;Integer, String&gt; entry = ring.ceilingEntry(hash(key));\nif (entry == null) entry = ring.firstEntry(); // wrap around\nreturn entry.getValue();</pre><br><strong>Used in:</strong> Cassandra (partition key routing), Riak, DynamoDB, CDN routing, load-balanced session stores."},

  {q:"What is the observability stack for a Java microservices system?",d:"medium", id:27,
     a:"Observability means understanding what your system is doing in production without manual debugging. Built on three pillars:<br><br><strong>1. Metrics (Micrometer + Prometheus + Grafana):</strong><br><pre>management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=prometheus\nmanagement.metrics.export.prometheus.enabled=true</pre>Track: request rate, error rate, latency percentiles (p50/p95/p99), JVM metrics, connection pool usage, custom business metrics.<br><br><strong>2. Logs (structured JSON → Loki/Elasticsearch):</strong><br><pre># Logstash encoder → JSON logs\nlogging.structured.format.console=json</pre>Index by traceId, userId, service name. MDC auto-injects contextual fields.<br><br><strong>3. Traces (Micrometer Tracing → Tempo/Jaeger):</strong><br><pre>spring.tracing.sampling.probability=0.1  # 10% in prod</pre>End-to-end request traces across services. Find which service is slow.<br><br><strong>Alerting:</strong> Grafana Alerts on Prometheus metrics — error rate &gt;1%, p95 latency &gt;500ms, JVM heap &gt;80%.<br><br><strong>Unified stack:</strong> Grafana Cloud (Loki + Tempo + Prometheus) or Datadog (all-in-one). Dashboards: USE method (Utilization, Saturation, Errors) per resource; RED method (Rate, Errors, Duration) per service."},

  {q:"How would you design a distributed ID generator (Twitter Snowflake)?",d:"hard", id:28,
     a:"A distributed ID generator produces globally unique, sortable 64-bit IDs without coordination — essential for distributed databases that can't use auto-increment.<br><br><strong>Snowflake ID structure (64 bits):</strong><br><pre>| 1 bit (unused) | 41 bits: timestamp (ms) | 10 bits: machine/datacenter ID | 12 bits: sequence |</pre><br><ul><li><strong>41 bits timestamp:</strong> milliseconds since epoch (2010) — ~69 years</li><li><strong>10 bits machine ID:</strong> datacenter (5 bits) + worker (5 bits) — 1024 machines</li><li><strong>12 bits sequence:</strong> counter within the same millisecond — 4096 IDs/ms per machine</li></ul><br><strong>Properties:</strong><ul><li>Time-ordered (sortable by creation time)</li><li>No coordination required between machines (each has unique machine ID)</li><li>4 million IDs/sec per machine (4096 per ms)</li></ul><br><strong>Java implementation skeleton:</strong><br><pre>public class SnowflakeIdGenerator {\n  private final long workerId;\n  private long sequence = 0L;\n  private long lastTimestamp = -1L;\n\n  public synchronized long nextId() {\n    long timestamp = System.currentTimeMillis();\n    if (timestamp == lastTimestamp) {\n      sequence = (sequence + 1) & 4095; // 12-bit mask\n      if (sequence == 0) timestamp = waitNextMillis(lastTimestamp); // seq overflow\n    } else {\n      sequence = 0;\n    }\n    lastTimestamp = timestamp;\n    return (timestamp << 22) | (workerId << 12) | sequence;\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Alternatives:</strong> UUIDv7 (time-ordered UUID), ULID, database sequences with pre-allocation."},

  {q:"What is back-pressure and how do you implement it in a streaming system?",d:"hard", id:29,
     a:"<strong>Back-pressure</strong> is a mechanism to prevent a fast producer from overwhelming a slow consumer — the consumer signals the producer to slow down or pause.<br><br><strong>Without back-pressure:</strong> producer floods consumer → consumer's queue grows unbounded → OutOfMemoryError or messages dropped.<br><br><strong>With back-pressure:</strong> consumer signals its capacity → producer respects it → system remains stable under load.<br><br><strong>Reactive Streams (Java Flow API, Project Reactor):</strong><br><pre>Flux.range(1, 1_000_000)\n  .map(this::slowTransform) // slow operation\n  .subscribe(new BaseSubscriber&lt;&gt;() {\n    @Override\n    protected void hookOnSubscribe(Subscription subscription) {\n      request(10); // request 10 items initially\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    protected void hookOnNext(Integer value) {\n      process(value);\n      request(1); // request 1 more after processing\n    }\n  });</pre><br>The subscriber controls flow — producer only sends what's requested.<br><br><strong>Kafka back-pressure:</strong> consumer controls <code>max.poll.records</code> and <code>fetch.max.wait.ms</code> — if consumer is slow, it fetches fewer records per poll.<br><br><strong>HTTP back-pressure:</strong> HTTP/2 flow control, TCP backpressure (receive window), or return <code>429 Too Many Requests</code> with <code>Retry-After</code>.<br><br><strong>Queue-based back-pressure:</strong> bounded queue with <code>CallerRunsPolicy</code> — when queue is full, producer thread processes the item itself (natural slowdown)."},

  {q:"How do you design exactly-once message processing end-to-end?",d:"hard", id:30,
     a:"True exactly-once semantics require three guarantees: (1) message delivery, (2) processing, (3) side effects (database writes, API calls) all happen exactly once — even under failures.<br><br><strong>Challenge:</strong> distributed systems can fail at any step. A message might be delivered twice, processed twice, or processed but not acked.<br><br><strong>Approach 1 — Idempotent processing with deduplication key:</strong><br><pre>@Transactional\npublic void processOrder(OrderEvent event) {\n  String idempotencyKey = event.getMessageId();\n\n  // Check if already processed\n  if (processedMessagesRepo.existsById(idempotencyKey)) {\n    log.info(\"Duplicate message, skipping\");\n    return;\n  }\n\n  // Process\n  Order order = orderRepo.save(event.toOrder());\n  paymentService.charge(order);\n\n  // Mark as processed (same transaction)\n  processedMessagesRepo.save(new ProcessedMessage(idempotencyKey, Instant.now()));\n}</pre><br>Store message ID in DB within the same transaction as business logic — if the transaction rolls back, the message ID isn't saved, so retry will reprocess correctly.<br><br><strong>Approach 2 — Transactional Outbox pattern:</strong><br>Instead of publishing events directly, write them to an <code>outbox</code> table in the same transaction as your business logic. A separate process (CDC or polling) reads the outbox and publishes to Kafka.<br><br><strong>Approach 3 — Kafka transactions (Kafka-to-Kafka only):</strong> consume, process, produce, and commit offsets atomically."},

  {q:"What is the difference between read-heavy and write-heavy system design?",d:"medium", id:31,
     a:"<strong>Read-heavy systems</strong> have far more reads than writes (e.g., news sites, product catalogs, social media feeds). <strong>Write-heavy systems</strong> have frequent writes (e.g., logging, sensor data, financial transactions).<br><br><strong>Read-heavy optimizations:</strong><ul><li><strong>Caching:</strong> Redis/CDN in front of DB — cache hit ratio &gt;90%</li><li><strong>Read replicas:</strong> scale horizontally (Postgres read replicas, Cassandra)</li><li><strong>Denormalization:</strong> precompute joins, materialized views</li><li><strong>Search indexes:</strong> Elasticsearch for full-text queries</li><li><strong>CDN:</strong> static assets + API responses cached at edge</li></ul><br><strong>Write-heavy optimizations:</strong><ul><li><strong>Write-ahead log:</strong> append-only, sequential writes (Kafka, Cassandra commit log)</li><li><strong>Batch writes:</strong> group writes into larger transactions (JDBC batch, Kafka produce batching)</li><li><strong>Sharding:</strong> distribute writes across partitions (Kafka partitions, Cassandra partition key)</li><li><strong>Asynchronous writes:</strong> ack before persisting to disk (faster but less durable)</li><li><strong>Time-series DB:</strong> InfluxDB, TimescaleDB optimized for append-only workloads</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Twitter:</strong> timeline reads are read-heavy (cached), tweet writes are write-heavy (fan-out to millions of followers' timelines asynchronously)."},

  {q:"How would you design a distributed cache from scratch?",d:"hard", id:32,
     a:"A distributed cache spreads data across multiple machines, providing horizontal scalability and fault tolerance.<br><br><strong>Core design decisions:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Data distribution (sharding):</strong><br><ul><li><strong>Consistent hashing:</strong> map keys to a ring, assign each machine a range. Minimizes data movement when machines are added/removed.</li><li><strong>Key partitioning:</strong> <code>hash(key) % N</code> — simple but all keys remap when N changes.</li></ul><br><strong>2. Replication for fault tolerance:</strong><br><ul><li>Each key stored on <code>R</code> replicas (e.g., 3). If one node dies, data still available.</li><li>Leader-based (writes go to leader, replicated to followers) or leaderless (client writes to all replicas).</li></ul><br><strong>3. Read/write quorums (tunable consistency):</strong><br><ul><li>Write to <code>W</code> replicas, read from <code>R</code> replicas.</li><li>If <code>W + R &gt; total replicas</code>, reads always see the latest write (strong consistency).</li><li>Example: 3 replicas, W=2, R=2 → overlapping guarantees latest value.</li></ul><br><strong>4. Eviction policy:</strong> LRU, LFU, TTL-based expiration.<br><br><strong>5. Network protocol:</strong> TCP (reliable) or UDP (low-latency, lossy).<br><br><strong>Pseudocode:</strong><br><pre>class DistributedCache {\n  ConsistentHashRing ring;\n\n  void put(String key, Object value) {\n    List&lt;Node&gt; replicas = ring.getNodes(key, replicationFactor);\n    for (Node node : replicas) {\n      node.send(PUT, key, value);\n    }\n  }\n\n  Object get(String key) {\n    List&lt;Node&gt; replicas = ring.getNodes(key, replicationFactor);\n    return replicas.get(0).send(GET, key); // or quorum read\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Real-world examples:</strong> Memcached (single-leader per key), Redis Cluster (sharded + replicated), DynamoDB (quorum-based)."},

  {q:"What is the CAP theorem and how do modern systems handle it?",d:"medium", id:33,
     a:"<strong>CAP theorem:</strong> in a distributed system experiencing a network partition (P), you must choose between Consistency (C) and Availability (A). You can't have all three simultaneously during a partition.<br><br><strong>C (Consistency):</strong> every read sees the most recent write — all nodes see the same data at the same time.<br><strong>A (Availability):</strong> every request receives a response (success or failure), even if some nodes are down.<br><strong>P (Partition tolerance):</strong> the system continues to function despite network failures splitting the cluster.<br><br><strong>Modern reality — PACELC:</strong> CAP assumes a partition is happening. PACELC extends it:<br><ul><li>If <strong>Partition</strong> → choose between <strong>Availability</strong> or <strong>Consistency</strong></li><li><strong>Else</strong> (no partition) → choose between <strong>Latency</strong> and <strong>Consistency</strong></li></ul><br><strong>Examples:</strong><br><ul><li><strong>CP (Consistency over Availability):</strong> traditional RDBMS, Zookeeper, etcd, HBase — reject writes during partition to maintain consistency</li><li><strong>AP (Availability over Consistency):</strong> Cassandra, DynamoDB, Riak — accept writes on both sides of partition, resolve conflicts later (eventual consistency)</li><li><strong>Tunable (modern approach):</strong> Cassandra allows per-query consistency level (QUORUM for strong consistency, ONE for high availability)</li></ul><br><strong>In practice:</strong> most systems are \"mostly available, eventually consistent\" — prioritize availability, tolerate temporary inconsistency, resolve conflicts with versioning or CRDTs."}
);

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"What is consistent hashing and why is it used in distributed systems?",d:"hard", id:34,
     a:"<strong>Consistent hashing</strong> solves the problem of minimizing key redistribution when nodes are added or removed from a distributed hash table.<br><br><strong>Traditional hashing problem:</strong><br><pre>// Simple hash-based partitioning\nnode_index = hash(key) % num_nodes\n// Adding/removing a node changes num_nodes → nearly ALL keys rehash to different nodes</pre>Impact: if you have 100 nodes and remove 1, ~99% of keys need to move (cache miss storm).<br><br><strong>Consistent hashing solution:</strong> map both nodes and keys to a ring (0 to 2³²). Each key is assigned to the <em>first node clockwise</em> from its position.<br><br><strong>Key properties:</strong><ul><li>Adding a node: only keys between the new node and the previous node need to move (~1/N keys)</li><li>Removing a node: only keys on that node need to move to the next node</li><li>Bounded impact: changes affect only immediate neighbors on the ring</li></ul><br><strong>Virtual nodes (vnodes):</strong> to avoid uneven distribution, each physical node is mapped to multiple points on the ring (e.g., 150 vnodes per node). Better load distribution when nodes have different capacities.<br><br><strong>Use cases:</strong><ul><li><strong>Distributed caches:</strong> Memcached, Redis Cluster (slot-based variant)</li><li><strong>CDNs:</strong> route requests to edge servers</li><li><strong>Distributed databases:</strong> Cassandra, DynamoDB (token ring)</li><li><strong>Load balancers:</strong> session affinity with dynamic backend pools</li></ul><br><strong>Trade-off:</strong> more complex than simple modulo hashing, but essential for elastic distributed systems where nodes frequently join/leave."}
);

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"Explain the Raft consensus algorithm and how it achieves distributed consensus.",d:"hard", id:35,
     a:"<strong>Raft</strong> is a consensus algorithm designed to be understandable. It ensures a cluster of nodes agrees on a replicated log of commands even when some nodes fail.<br><br><strong>Core concepts:</strong><br><br><strong>Leader election:</strong> nodes exist in 3 states: Follower, Candidate, Leader. One Leader at a time.<ul><li>Followers wait for heartbeats from the Leader</li><li>If heartbeat timeout expires → Follower becomes Candidate</li><li>Candidate requests votes; if it gets majority → becomes Leader</li><li>Leader sends heartbeats to maintain authority</li></ul><br><strong>Log replication:</strong><ol><li>Client sends command to Leader</li><li>Leader appends to its log and replicates to Followers (AppendEntries RPC)</li><li>Once majority have replicated → Leader commits the entry</li><li>Leader notifies Followers to commit; they apply to their state machines</li><li>Leader responds to client</li></ol><br><strong>Safety guarantees:</strong><ul><li><strong>Election Safety:</strong> at most one leader per term</li><li><strong>Log Matching:</strong> if two logs contain an entry with the same index and term, all preceding entries are identical</li><li><strong>Leader Completeness:</strong> if a log entry is committed in a term, it will be present in all future leader logs</li></ul><br><strong>Split-brain prevention:</strong> requires <em>majority quorum</em> (N/2 + 1). A cluster of 5 nodes tolerates 2 failures; 3 nodes tolerate 1 failure. Cannot have two leaders because neither can get majority.<br><br><strong>Comparison with Paxos:</strong> Raft is easier to understand (single leader model) while providing equivalent guarantees. Paxos has no inherent leader and is notoriously complex.<br><br><strong>Real-world usage:</strong><ul><li><strong>etcd</strong> — Kubernetes' coordination store</li><li><strong>Consul</strong> — service discovery and configuration</li><li><strong>CockroachDB</strong> — distributed SQL database</li></ul>"}
);

SEC_HLD.qs.push(
  {q:"What are Bloom Filters and when would you use them in distributed systems?",d:"medium", id:36,
     a:"A <strong>Bloom filter</strong> is a space-efficient probabilistic data structure for <em>set membership testing</em>. It can definitively say \"not in set\" but may give false positives for \"in set\".<br><br><strong>How it works:</strong><ol><li>Initialize a bit array of size M (all zeros)</li><li>Use K independent hash functions</li><li><strong>Add:</strong> hash the item K times, set those K bits to 1</li><li><strong>Check:</strong> hash the item K times, if <em>all</em> K bits are 1 → \"probably in set\"; if <em>any</em> bit is 0 → \"definitely NOT in set\"</li></ol><br><strong>Key properties:</strong><ul><li>No false negatives (if it says \"no\", it's definitely not there)</li><li>False positives possible (if it says \"yes\", it might be wrong)</li><li>Cannot remove items (bits are shared by multiple items)</li><li>Extremely space-efficient: ~10 bits per element for 1% false positive rate</li></ul><br><strong>False positive rate formula:</strong> <code>(1 - e^(-kn/m))^k</code> where k=hash functions, n=items, m=bit array size.<br><br><strong>Use cases in distributed systems:</strong><ul><li><strong>Cache filtering:</strong> CDNs use Bloom filters to avoid cache lookups for items definitely not cached (saves disk seeks)</li><li><strong>Duplicate detection:</strong> check if a URL has been crawled without storing all URLs</li><li><strong>Database query optimization:</strong> Cassandra uses Bloom filters per SSTable to avoid reading files that definitely don't contain the key</li><li><strong>Blockchain:</strong> Bitcoin uses Bloom filters for lightweight SPV (Simplified Payment Verification) clients</li><li><strong>Distributed deduplication:</strong> quickly check if a file chunk exists across nodes</li></ul><br><strong>Variants:</strong><ul><li><strong>Counting Bloom Filter:</strong> uses counters instead of bits → supports deletion</li><li><strong>Scalable Bloom Filter:</strong> dynamically grows as more items are added</li><li><strong>Cuckoo Filter:</strong> supports deletion and has better lookup performance</li></ul><br><strong>Trade-off:</strong> trades accuracy for space. Choose Bloom filter when: (1) false positives are acceptable, (2) space is constrained, (3) negative results are common."}
);